The most important step in planting healthy perennials is preparing the soil. Most perennials prefer rich, deep, well-drained soil. Evaluate your garden soil to determine how to amend it for perennials. If your soil has high concentrations of clay, add peat, compost and sand. If your soil has high concentrations of sand, add compost to add nutrients and create a richer soil. Organic matter like manure, compost, perlite and peat moss are beneficial to most types of garden soils. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/fe\/Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/f\/fe\/Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/aid2005766-v4-728px-Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Dig the planting area to a minimum depth of about 8 inches (20.3 cm) using a spade or pitchfork. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/92\/Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/9\/92\/Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/aid2005766-v4-728px-Plant-Perennials-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Spread organic matter directly on top of the existing soil and work it into the ground using a shovel or pitchfork. Insert the shovel or pitchfork into the ground, pull out the shovel filled with dirt and flip the shovel over, dumping garden soil on top of the organic matter. Repeat throughout the garden area until the organic matter is thoroughly mixed into the garden soil.

Most container-bound perennials at garden centers come with tags indicating growing conditions required for healthy plants. Examine the tags to ensure the perennials you purchase will grow well in the planting bed you prepared. Consider the height of each plant. Keep in mind that taller plants may block the view (and light) of shorter plants. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/0/00/Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/aid2005766-v4-728px-Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider the bloom color of the perennials. Bright colored plants can brighten up shady spots, while dark colored plants may add depth and texture to a full sun garden. Some gardeners select color palettes for their gardens. If you choose a color palette, ensure the bloom color of the perennial complements your palette. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/b3/Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/aid2005766-v4-728px-Plant-Perennials-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
